# Source: archive/kyp-snapshot/capturedPackets/capture_1.rar (frame 222).
# 14-byte frame on the wire: 4-byte header + 10-byte ServerRedirect
# payload. Header was "0E 00 36 00" (length=14 LE, opcode=0x36 LE).
# Below is JUST the 10-byte payload -- the part DecodeInbound consumes.
#
# Decoded fields (per ServerRedirectCodec wire format -- all three
# fields are little-endian on the wire; see codec doc-comment for the
# byte-order derivation):
#   sector_id  bytes 5F B0 00 00 -- LE-read = 0x0000B05F = 45151. The
#              matching MasterJoin (sent by the client moments earlier)
#              carried ToSectorID = 0x0000B05F (BE), so the value
#              round-trips cleanly when sector_id is decoded LE.
#              Cross-checked against three other capture frames
#              (capture_1 frames 656, 1062 and capture_2 frame 222),
#              each of which shows sector_id LE-on-wire matching the
#              prior MasterJoin's host-order ToSectorID. Earlier
#              versions of this codec read this field as big-endian and
#              produced a garbage index that the Win32 client looked up
#              in its sector pool, got NULL, then crashed on the next
#              vtable dispatch during the sector handoff.
#   ip_address bytes 2E E8 99 9F -- LE-read int = 0x9F99E82E, fed into a
#              sockaddr_in.s_addr it inet_ntoa's to 159.153.232.46.
#              Consistent with the source IP family (master server was
#              at 159.153.232.146) and with the codec's "LE int -> BE
#              bytes -> IPAddress(byte[])" decode.
#   port       bytes AC 0D -- LE = 0x0DAC = 3500. Matches our
#              PROXY_LOCAL_TCP_PORT, suggesting retail also used 3500
#              for sector traffic.
5F B0 00 00
2E E8 99 9F
AC 0D
